President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation declaring October 2014 as National Substance Abuse Prevention Month. The proclamation emphasizes the negative impact of substance abuse on families, schools, and communities, as well as the importance of preventing substance use before it begins. The proclamation highlights the Obama Administration's support for evidence-based education and outreach programs that target young people, as well as the investment in local coalitions through the Drug-Free Communities Support Program. It also emphasizes the role of parents, mentors, and community members in modeling a healthy lifestyle and educating children about the dangers of drug and alcohol use. The proclamation calls on all Americans to engage in programs and activities that promote comprehensive substance abuse prevention efforts in their communities.